<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="322" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[178,1085,859,911]" pageId="5" pageNumber="322">Etymology: The specific epithet is an adjective derived from the Latin noun nasus (nose) and alludes to the nose-shaped ventral process of the aedeagus.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="322" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[178,1085,926,1036]" pageId="5" pageNumber="322">
Description: Body length 
<quantity box="[538,618,926,947]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="5" pageNumber="322" unit="mm" value="2.9">2.9 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 
<quantity box="[825,905,926,948]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="322" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
. Coloration: head and pronotum dark reddish-brown; elytra reddish; abdomen reddish-brown, with the posterior portion of segment VII and segments VIII-X reddish-yellow; legs reddishyellow; antennae reddish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[178,1086,1051,1190]" pageId="5" pageNumber="322">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[249,326,1051,1073]" captionStart="Figs 14-21" captionStartId="6.[178,218,1403,1425]" captionTargetBox="[178,1063,212,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-1@6.[178,1082,212,1378]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 14-21: Hypomedon nasutus nov.sp. (14-17) and H. bicornutus nov.sp. (18-21): (1-2) forebody; (3-10) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (11-13) male sternite VIII. Scale bars: 14, 18: 0.5 mm; 15-17, 19-21: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5416281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5416281/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="322">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) 1.23 times as broad as long; punctation coarse, moderately dense, and umbilicate; interstices with pronounced microsculpture. Eyes approximately 0.7 times as long as postocular region in dorsal view. Antenna: antennomere III approximately as broad as long; antennomeres IV-X of gradually increasing width and increasingly transverse; X approximately twice as broad as long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[178,1085,1205,1286]" pageId="5" pageNumber="322">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[292,367,1205,1228]" captionStart="Figs 14-21" captionStartId="6.[178,218,1403,1425]" captionTargetBox="[178,1063,212,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-1@6.[178,1082,212,1378]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 14-21: Hypomedon nasutus nov.sp. (14-17) and H. bicornutus nov.sp. (18-21): (1-2) forebody; (3-10) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (11-13) male sternite VIII. Scale bars: 14, 18: 0.5 mm; 15-17, 19-21: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5416281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5416281/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="322">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) 1.07 times as broad as long and 0.94 times as broad as head; punctation similar to that of head, but somewhat denser; interstices with pronounced microsculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[178,1085,1301,1353]" pageId="5" pageNumber="322">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[256,332,1301,1323]" captionStart="Figs 14-21" captionStartId="6.[178,218,1403,1425]" captionTargetBox="[178,1063,212,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-1@6.[178,1082,212,1378]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 14-21: Hypomedon nasutus nov.sp. (14-17) and H. bicornutus nov.sp. (18-21): (1-2) forebody; (3-10) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (11-13) male sternite VIII. Scale bars: 14, 18: 0.5 mm; 15-17, 19-21: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5416281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5416281/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="322">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as pronotum; punctation very dense and moderately fine; interstices without microsculpture. Hind wings apparently fully developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[178,1085,1368,1448]" pageId="5" pageNumber="322">Abdomen narrower than elytra; punctation dense and fine on anterior, sparse and even finer on posterior tergites; interstices with shallow microsculpture; posterior margin of tergite VII with palisade fringe.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[178,1085,1464,1544]" pageId="5" pageNumber="322">
♂: sternite VII unmodified; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[621,697,1464,1486]" captionStart="Figs 14-21" captionStartId="6.[178,218,1403,1425]" captionTargetBox="[178,1063,212,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-1@6.[178,1082,212,1378]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 14-21: Hypomedon nasutus nov.sp. (14-17) and H. bicornutus nov.sp. (18-21): (1-2) forebody; (3-10) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (11-13) male sternite VIII. Scale bars: 14, 18: 0.5 mm; 15-17, 19-21: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5416281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5416281/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="322">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) weakly transverse, posterior margin convex, in the middle very indistinctly concave; aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[801,915,1493,1515]" captionStart="Figs 14-21" captionStartId="6.[178,218,1403,1425]" captionTargetBox="[178,1063,212,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-1@6.[178,1082,212,1378]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 14-21: Hypomedon nasutus nov.sp. (14-17) and H. bicornutus nov.sp. (18-21): (1-2) forebody; (3-10) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (11-13) male sternite VIII. Scale bars: 14, 18: 0.5 mm; 15-17, 19-21: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5416281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5416281/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="322">Figs 16-17</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[932,1025,1493,1514]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="322" unit="mm" value="0.32">0.32 mm</quantity>
long, with relatively short ventral process of characteristic shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5416281" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5416281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5416281/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="323" startId="6.[178,218,1403,1425]" targetBox="[178,1063,212,1366]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[178,1086,1403,1471]" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[178,281,1403,1425]" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">Figs 14-21</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Assing, 2016" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2016" box="[296,485,1403,1425]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nasutus" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis box="[296,485,1403,1425]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">Hypomedon nasutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[494,561,1404,1425]" pageId="6" pageNumber="323" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[577,630,1403,1424]" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">14-17</emphasis>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Assing, 2016" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2016" box="[689,818,1403,1425]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicornutus" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis box="[689,818,1403,1425]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">H. bicornutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[827,894,1404,1425]" pageId="6" pageNumber="323" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[910,964,1403,1424]" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">18-21</emphasis>
): (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[994,1024,1403,1424]" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">1-2</emphasis>
) forebody; (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[244,286,1426,1447]" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">3-10</emphasis>
) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[674,727,1426,1447]" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">11-13</emphasis>
) male sternite VIII. Scale bars: 14, 18: 0.5 mm; 15-17, 19-21: 0.2 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="324" pageId="6" pageNumber="323" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[178,1085,1485,1595]" lastBlockId="7.[178,1085,219,358]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="324" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">
Comparative notes: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2016" box="[533,743,1485,1506]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nasutus">
<emphasis box="[533,743,1485,1506]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">Hypomedon nasutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from the externally similar 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="BORDONI" baseAuthorityYear="1980" box="[318,445,1514,1536]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="galilaeus">
<emphasis box="[318,445,1514,1536]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">H. galilaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="WOLLASTON" baseAuthorityYear="1857" box="[500,655,1514,1536]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="debilicornis">
<emphasis box="[500,655,1514,1536]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="323">H. debilicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the completely different shape of the ventral process of the aedeagus, the different shape of the male sternite VIII, a more transverse antennomere X, and larger punctures on the pronotum. The aedeagus of the new species is most similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authority="(KOCH, 1934)" baseAuthorityName="KOCH" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[570,840,219,241]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niloticus">
<emphasis box="[570,689,219,240]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="324">H. niloticus</emphasis>
(KOCH, 1934)
</taxonomicName>
, but the ventral process and the sclerotized dorso-apical structure are of different shapes. Moreover, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2016" box="[974,1085,249,270]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nasutus">
<emphasis box="[974,1085,249,270]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="324">H. nasutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="KOCH" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[314,435,277,299]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niloticus">
<emphasis box="[314,435,277,299]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="324">H. niloticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by coarser and denser punctation of the head and pronotum, larger eyes, and by a less transverse and posteriorly only indistinctly concave male sternite VIII. For illustrations of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="KOCH" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[474,592,336,358]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypomedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niloticus">
<emphasis box="[474,592,336,358]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="324">H. niloticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
see 
<bibRefCitation author="ASSING V" box="[637,790,336,358]" pageId="7" pageNumber="324" pagination="1161 - 1173" refId="ref4398" refString="ASSING V. (2009): On the identity of some Acanthoglossa and Hypomedon species, primarily from the Mediterranean region (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Linzer Biologische Beitrage 41 (2): 1161 - 1173." type="journal article" year="2009">ASSING (2009)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
